WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.960
And in doing so, we identified a couple key elements.

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:14.400
Firstly, we were repeating the same ggplot theme elements within a file and across multiple

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:15.400
different files.

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:19.360
Meaning we were copying code chunks every single time we were creating a new script

00:00:19.360 --> 00:00:20.559
and new plot.

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:23.400
Importantly, this wasn't standard across the board.

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:28.400
So if I were creating a new plot, I would open up my script, copy in this code chunk,

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:30.680
and then make a small modification.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:35.040
Let's say I wanted to increase the line weight of my axis or something like that.

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:39.000
That's not to say then that the next person who goes and copies my code is going to keep

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.400
the same things and make the same customizations.

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:45.840
So we were having these repetitions, but also lacked uniformity across the board.

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:52.099
Secondly, we were repeating hex colors throughout our scripts and had, as Aaron mentioned, multiple

00:00:52.099 --> 00:00:55.439
different colors that were being used that we were explicitly calling out with their

00:00:55.439 --> 00:00:58.880
hex code each time.

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:04.160
And finally, our team had custom export parameters for the size and DPI of our plots that we

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:06.639
were using for presentations.

00:01:06.639 --> 00:01:10.639
And while we had this ggsave function that was ready to go at the end of each of our

00:01:10.639 --> 00:01:16.080
scripts, we still had to copy that every time we were creating a new script.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:19.599
And so doing this inventory allowed us to then parse through our code base and make

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:24.400
decisions about what we wanted to keep that we would then pull into our standard plot

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:26.800
elements going forward.

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:32.080
So here you have a mock-up of our notes and sketches throughout this process and the decisions

00:01:32.080 --> 00:01:33.839
that we made about formatting.

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:39.360
And we took it a step further and specifically ascribed for each plot element what we wanted

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:41.839
those decisions to be.

00:01:41.839 --> 00:01:46.000
And the goal of this slide is not for you to be able to see every single element on

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:50.239
this plot, but to understand our thought process behind what we were doing.

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:54.239
We went through and specifically said for the title, this is going to be in all capital

00:01:54.239 --> 00:01:58.400
letters, 14-point font, in this very specific shade of dark gray.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:02.800
And we did this for every element of the plot, from the caption to the annotation to grid

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:06.639
lines and even to the source note at the bottom of the plot.

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:11.039
This effort to better document and understand our previous work allowed us to then move

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:15.520
into ggplot seamlessly with this mock-up and start building our custom refinements on top

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:18.720
of what already existed in ggplot.

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:24.639
We focused on three main buckets to make these refinements to our custom plot branding.

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:29.919
Starting with the plot elements themselves, we were really motivated to adhere to data

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:33.520
visualization principles, namely to declutter our plots and show the data.

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:39.199
To do so, we really liked the minimal from ggplot as a great starting point for this

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:45.440
and leveraged the replace function from ggplot to then make small refinements on top of the

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:48.720
minimal based on our notes from all of our previous code.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:55.039
And so this was making adjustments to things from title and subtitle all the way down to

00:02:55.039 --> 00:02:56.320
things like ticks and margins.

00:02:57.679 --> 00:03:01.279
For typeface, this was one of the ways that we could really distinctively make this style

00:03:01.279 --> 00:03:01.679
our own.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:06.160
Our agency has a branding guide, and while this branding guide doesn't necessarily discuss

00:03:06.160 --> 00:03:10.479
too much about data visualization principles, it does denote a specific web font to use,

00:03:10.479 --> 00:03:11.600
which was Source Sans Pro.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:17.199
And we really wanted to use this font instead of the three default fonts in ggplot.

00:03:17.199 --> 00:03:22.399
And to do so, we used the extra font package in gr-devices, which allowed us to build in

00:03:22.399 --> 00:03:27.520
our custom font, Source Sans Pro, into our existing R package.

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:33.520
And so by packaging all of these elements into their own central theme and building

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:37.520
in a custom font for our package, we were able to pull all of these elements together

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:40.720
into one simple function called si-style.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:45.039
And the idea behind si-style is that any user could pick this up and pipe this into

00:03:45.039 --> 00:03:50.880
their existing ggplot code and then immediately be able to standardize their plot elements

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:51.919
to our style.

00:03:51.919 --> 00:03:56.399
So visual hierarchy, axes, whitespace, the likes, while still remaining flexible and

00:03:56.399 --> 00:03:57.600
customizable to the user.

00:03:58.479 --> 00:04:01.199
So the last leg of the stool is color, right?

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:03.679
We needed to create something that really made it our own.

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:08.559
So as Krishna mentioned, we have this branding guide that doesn't talk about visualization

00:04:08.559 --> 00:04:12.000
for our agency, but we wanted to use some of the colors, right?

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:13.759
There's some nice colors going on here.

00:04:13.759 --> 00:04:18.079
There's just not a big enough palette to make it useful for data visualization, nor

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:20.959
is there enough contrast to really make this accessible.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:22.399
So those were our two priorities.

00:04:22.959 --> 00:04:28.720
So we used this as a starting place to work from, and we picked two of the USAID-branded

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:29.200
colors.

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:38.000
And from there, we used free software, Adobe Color, Palatable, and VizPalette to play with

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.519
the hue and saturation of those two colors to then adjust them, do additional adjustments,

00:04:43.519 --> 00:04:46.320
and then make sure that there was enough contrast going on.

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:51.359
And as a result, we came up with our own colors that were similar, yet distinct from the original

00:04:51.359 --> 00:04:53.200
and had enough contrast in them.

00:04:53.920 --> 00:05:00.160
And then from there, we built out a larger set of colors and a gray, and then each of

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:02.000
those then had lights that we could use.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:07.359
And then we defined additional colors for each of our plot elements that we could use

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:08.399
to standardize them.

00:05:09.279 --> 00:05:13.359
If you're feeling a little overwhelmed by having to make all these decisions about color,

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:17.279
we really, really, really love Lisa Charlotte-Mooth.

00:05:17.279 --> 00:05:22.640
She has some unbelievable resources that we relied on in talking about color for data

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:26.559
visualization and how to put together color for a style guide.

00:05:26.559 --> 00:05:31.119
And she's working on a book right now that I think is coming out later this year.

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:37.119
So with those three pillars in place, we were able to create a package, right?

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:38.079
We started small.

00:05:38.079 --> 00:05:43.119
We had our SI style that Karishma mentioned earlier, and we're able to have a good starting

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:44.880
place for something everybody could use.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:50.399
And to make it so that everybody could use this, boom, we pushed it up to GitHub, and

00:05:50.399 --> 00:05:55.839
it became accessible not just to our team, but to our colleagues in the missions and

00:05:55.839 --> 00:05:58.079
our other agencies that we're working with.

00:05:58.959 --> 00:06:04.559
So we started, like I said, with SI style, got the job done, and then we expanded from

00:06:04.559 --> 00:06:04.799
there.

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:12.160
That SI style has about nine different alterations that you can use just to be flexible.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:17.200
And then as we realized there were more things that we were repeating, we built out additional

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:22.399
functionality to interpolate colors and to make sure that our exports were the same every

00:06:22.399 --> 00:06:26.320
single time, regardless of whether Karishma was doing it or I was.

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:33.040
So I think everybody, right, is familiar with based UG plot and those colors, right?

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:36.959
You would not be, you know, if you've ever used it, looks pretty standard.

00:06:36.959 --> 00:06:39.920
And so it gets the job done.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:45.519
But to those points that Laura was talking about earlier, we added our own style here

00:06:45.519 --> 00:06:51.040
to help at a baseline provide some differences to help with focus and other things.

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:56.480
So we have scale fill SI that we've just added on top of GG plot, which is providing the

00:06:56.480 --> 00:07:00.559
colors by default from our color palette, which then the user could adjust the different

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:02.079
colors on our palette.

00:07:02.079 --> 00:07:07.440
And then lastly, this SI style grid, which is providing a wide grid instead of just the

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:08.880
standard SI style.

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:11.679
And then you're seeing changes in our title, our caption.

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:14.480
The strip text at the top looks different.

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:17.519
The placement of the legend.

00:07:17.519 --> 00:07:22.160
So all of these are conscious decisions that we're doing to make declutter our graphs and

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:23.359
make them more legible.

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:27.119
So the great thing about this is it just works, right?

00:07:27.119 --> 00:07:30.160
We don't have to think about these things every single time.

00:07:30.160 --> 00:07:34.720
You just add a line or two to your GG plot code, and it just works.

00:07:36.559 --> 00:07:40.399
The last piece of the puzzle for us was to take all of this work that we had built in

00:07:40.399 --> 00:07:43.839
the R environment and package it into a tool agnostic style guide.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:49.279
So we had a tool that works really, really well and powerfully in R to standardize our

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:52.320
plot elements and apply visual coherence to our visuals.

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:56.079
But the next step was to think about how we could socialize this more broadly within our

00:07:56.079 --> 00:08:00.239
team and make this something that was useful to folks, regardless of their data visualization

00:08:00.239 --> 00:08:01.119
platform of choice.

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:05.200
We also recognized that the glitter package alone was not enough.

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:07.519
Let's take this visual, for instance.

00:08:07.519 --> 00:08:13.600
This is a pet bar plot that's built in Excel, and it's trying to convey the point of funding

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:15.920
being transitioned to local partners in the blue.

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:22.000
And while we can leverage the glitter package to apply our standard plot elements, to add

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.760
some visual coherence with our font, colors, and white space, there's still something

00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:28.799
missing from this visual to really effectively tell the story.

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:33.760
And that missing piece is the intentional use of data visualization principles throughout

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:34.719
your plot.

00:08:34.719 --> 00:08:39.599
Things like sorting your data to more effectively show your point, or encoding the key takeaway

00:08:39.599 --> 00:08:44.080
message into the title to make it meaningful, or strategically leveraging labels to add

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:45.119
context to your plot.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:49.119
All things that can't be built into an R package.

00:08:49.119 --> 00:08:53.520
And this really solidified for us the need to have one resource that anyone can come

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:58.400
to that explains why we made the choices we made for our custom plot elements, but

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:04.239
also outlines the data visualization principles that you need to be thinking about when making

00:09:04.239 --> 00:09:05.200
plots on your own.

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:10.080
We wanted this to be like a paint by numbers, if you will, where no matter where you are

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:14.400
in your data visualization journey, you have tools and resources that you can easily build

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:16.719
upon and have guideposts for what you're doing and why.

00:09:17.840 --> 00:09:20.479
And so our data visualization style guide was born.

00:09:20.479 --> 00:09:24.880
And this style guide takes you through all of the elements that you should be thinking

00:09:24.880 --> 00:09:27.599
about when creating a data visualization of your own.

00:09:27.599 --> 00:09:35.119
It also details out the choices that our team made when creating our custom themes and colors,

00:09:35.119 --> 00:09:41.359
and acts as one central resource for our entire office of 300 people to come to as their data

00:09:41.359 --> 00:09:42.320
visualization hub.

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:44.320
So what?

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:45.200
Where do we go from here?

00:09:45.919 --> 00:09:51.039
Well, before Glitter and the style guide, our teams were working in silos and often

00:09:51.039 --> 00:09:57.359
were creating products that lacked visual coherence and ended up creating a lot of cognitive

00:09:57.359 --> 00:10:00.719
load anytime you were looking at your presentations.

00:10:00.719 --> 00:10:05.039
And while this before and after is zoomed out, you can still see a little bit more visual

00:10:05.039 --> 00:10:07.119
coherence in the slide deck on the bottom.

00:10:07.679 --> 00:10:12.960
In addition to this just looking nice and professional, our team has seen numerous benefits

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:14.719
since the introduction of these tools.

00:10:16.159 --> 00:10:21.359
Firstly, our team has seen significant efficiency gains since the introduction of the style

00:10:21.359 --> 00:10:23.119
guide and the R package.

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:27.919
Instead now of all of our colleagues having to reinvent the wheel every single time, they

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:31.679
have a foundation that they can build off of and can spend more time focusing on the

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:32.880
analytic questions at hand.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.359
This style guide has also enabled us to create unified branding within our team and recognition

00:10:39.359 --> 00:10:41.359
of products that are coming out of our office.

00:10:41.359 --> 00:10:47.280
And as mentioned in the previous talk, having visualizations that look nice matters.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:51.919
And it also improves your data storytelling and the quality of your analytic products.

00:10:52.799 --> 00:10:57.039
From a visibility standpoint, our team has been able to share what we've learned throughout

00:10:57.039 --> 00:11:01.119
this process with other teams in the federal space who are looking to implement similar

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:02.799
processes within their organizations.

00:11:03.679 --> 00:11:08.479
And finally, having these central data visualization resources makes for easier onboarding of

00:11:08.479 --> 00:11:09.039
new staff.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:14.000
We can speak firsthand that these resources do not stand alone within our team.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:19.200
It's created a community of collaboration within our office and also lowers the barriers

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:23.200
to entry for folks who are looking to get engaged in data visualization or even in the

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:23.760
R space.

00:11:25.679 --> 00:11:29.039
So all in all, these processes take time and they take effort.

00:11:29.039 --> 00:11:32.640
But in doing so, you're not only enabling yourself to succeed, but others in your team

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:34.960
to succeed well into the future.

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:40.320
Our framework was to first do an inventory of our universe of outputs and workflows and

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:44.799
find pieces that we could build upon and then move those into ggplot to make refinements

00:11:44.799 --> 00:11:48.239
to our plot elements, typeface, and any decisions to be made about color.

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:52.880
And then finally, take all of that work and package it into a tool agnostic style guide

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:58.799
that you can share more broadly within your teams and create and generate more buy-in

00:11:58.799 --> 00:12:00.000
and promote accessibility.

00:12:00.799 --> 00:12:04.559
We've shared this framework with you today in the hopes that this will be useful and

00:12:04.559 --> 00:12:08.719
beneficial to you and your teams so that next time, you don't need to start from a

00:12:08.719 --> 00:12:09.440
blank canvas.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.520
Rather, instead of starting from scratch, you have a palette that you can work off of,

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:19.359
you have tools that can help you get there, and guideposts for what you're doing and why.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.359
Thank you all for coming today, and we hope that this talk has inspired you to add a touch

00:12:23.359 --> 00:12:25.200
of glitter to your data visualization workforce.

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:32.719
Thank you.

00:12:32.719 --> 00:12:34.159
Thank you both for a great talk.

00:12:34.719 --> 00:12:36.479
And we have time for a couple of questions.

00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:42.080
One question is, have you thought about glitter for Plotly?

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:45.359
So I guess people are interested in, you know, interactive.

00:12:45.359 --> 00:12:45.919
Sure.

00:12:45.919 --> 00:12:49.760
I mean, we haven't, but I mean, it's kind of a next extension that we have all this

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:50.320
built out.

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:51.119
That wouldn't be hard.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:53.520
Okay, a second question.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:58.320
How can none, I guess you partially answered this already, but how can none of our users

00:12:58.320 --> 00:12:59.359
use your resources?

00:13:01.200 --> 00:13:07.599
Yeah, I think the style guide is really that bridge to allow folks to engage in the R space

00:13:07.599 --> 00:13:10.239
with this, but also pull this into their other visualization tools.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:16.400
So our team also works at CrossTableau and Excel, and we've been able to pull these guiding

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:19.119
principles into our work in those software as well.

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:23.679
How do you convince others at your organization to use your package?

00:13:24.799 --> 00:13:25.359
We don't.

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:33.679
So we, within our office, have been able to basically showcase what this can do, but we

00:13:33.679 --> 00:13:37.200
are in a federal space where there are these branding and guidelines.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:39.440
And so most of our work is internal.

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:43.919
And so we're able to kind of skirt around that for now by just doing this internally.

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:50.159
Lastly, what was the trickiest part about the process to set up your design in terms

00:13:50.159 --> 00:13:53.840
of selling it to the office as well as making decisions?

00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:56.080
It's tough.

00:13:56.080 --> 00:13:59.359
I mean, I think just the time, like communication that it has to take.

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:03.599
You have to be able to show your product and the difference that it's going to make, and

00:14:03.599 --> 00:14:08.559
then also get some buy-in from the people you're working with to make those changes

00:14:08.559 --> 00:14:11.280
from doing what they're doing to the product.

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:16.000
To make those changes from doing what they're doing to kind of buy into the rest of this.

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:18.320
Thank you very much.

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:22.880
Thank you.

